[[File:Ono-jinja (Nankoku) torii.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Torii]]
'''Ono Shrine''' (おのじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Koren, Okō-chō, {{ill|lt=Nankoku|Q861621|WD=Q861621|1=Nankoku, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Kōchi Prefecture|Q134093|WD=Q134093|1=Kōchi Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The shrine enshrines the following one deity{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.
* {{ill|lt=Ama-tarashihiko-kuni-oshi-hito-no-Mikoto|Q11443593|WD=Q11443593|1=Prince Ametarashihiko}} - ancestral deity of the {{ill|lt=Ono clan|Q11464141|WD=Q11464141|1=Ono clan}}.

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. Tradition says it began when the {{ill|lt=Ono clan|Q11464141|WD=Q11464141|1=Ono clan}} that settled this area worshiped their ancestral deity{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. However, there is also a theory that the shrine name “Ono” comes from a place name rather than the clan name{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. Around the shrine are many {{ill|lt=kofun|Q1141225|WD=Q1141225|1=Kofun}}, including {{ill|lt=Koren Kofun|Q20044371|WD=Q20044371|1=Koren Kofun}}{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' compiled in {{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}} ({{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5), the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' lists “Ono Shrine” in {{ill|lt=Nagaoka District|Q1132123|WD=Q1132123|1=Nagaoka District, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Tosa Province|Q857330|WD=Q857330|1=Tosa Province}}, and this is identified with this shrine{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|WD=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}}, Ono Castle was built on the hill at the current site. It is said that when {{ill|lt=Kagawa Chikakazu|Q3676181|WD=Q3676181|1=Kagawa Chikakazu}}, second son of {{ill|lt=Chōsokabe Motochika|Q1070082|WD=Q1070082|1=Chōsokabe Motochika}}, returned after the decline of the Kagawa family, he was given that old Ono Castle{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. Medieval and early modern documents such as ''Nanroshi'' also contain entries calling it “Toyooka Daimyōjin,” apparently confusing it with Toyooka Daimyōjin enshrined in the precincts{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was ranked as a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}{{Sfn|Ono Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

